      Bill Hwang
   =20
 =20
Bill Hwang was charged with market manipulation because his family office, =
Archegos Capital Management, bought a ton of shares of about a dozen stocks=
, as sloppily as possible, with the effect and apparent intention of making=
 those stocks go up. Yesterday a jury convicted him.
  [4]
=C2=A0After the trial, it seems reasonably clear that Hwang wanted to buy a=
 ton of those stocks to push their prices up, and he told his trader to do =
so. He wasn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0just=C2=A0buying lots of those stocks because he=
 liked them, with the accidental side effect of pushing up the prices; he r=
eally wanted to push up the prices, and bought in an aggressive manner to a=
chieve that goal.=C2=A0And that=E2=80=99s probably illegal: Buying a ton of=
 stock with the intention of pushing up the price is market manipulation; i=
t=E2=80=99s causing the price of the stock to reflect something other than =
real supply and demand.
  [5]
Still, the trial is unsatisfying. Normally, in this sort of market manipula=
tion =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Copen market manipulation,=E2=80=9D where you a=
rtificially inflate the price of a stock just by buying a lot of it, withou=
t also going around telling lies about how the company has a cure for cance=
r or whatever =E2=80=94 you also have=C2=A0some plan to make money.=C2=A0Ri=
ght? It=E2=80=99s easy, with enough money, to make a stock go up: You just =
buy a lot of it, and the price will go up. But then what? Then you sell a l=
ot of it, and the price will go right back down. You have big paper profits=
 on the way up, but you cannot realize those profits, and by the time you s=
ell the stock you end up losing money. This certainly happened to Hwang: He=
 started off with hundreds of millions of dollars, briefly manipulated his =
way to $36 billion, sold his stocks and ended up at zero.There=C2=A0are=C2=
=A0ways to make money from this sort of market manipulation, but they requi=
re some sort of additional plan. We have talked about Avi Eisenberg, the Ma=
ngo Markets guy, who artificially inflated the price of a crypto token (by =
buying a lot of it), created large paper profits on a derivative position, =
and then was able to withdraw those profits from a somewhat dumb decentrali=
zed finance protocol.=C2=A0That=E2=80=99s=C2=A0how you do market manipulati=
on: Buy a lot of a thing, yes, but also (1) have a bigger derivative positi=
on that profits from your buying and/or (2) trick someone into lending you =
money against your artificially inflated asset so you don=E2=80=99t have to=
 sell it and drive down the price. (Eisenberg was also convicted.)=C2=A0Tha=
t=C2=A0makes sense: You inflate the price of the thing, and you have some p=
lan to make money.From the beginning, the mystery of Bill Hwang is that the=
re has never been any real evidence that he had a plan to make money. He bo=
ught stocks, he pushed them up, he had paper profits, he had capacity to wi=
thdraw or borrow against some of those paper profits, and he plowed basical=
ly all of them back into buying more of the same stocks. He never took his =
foot off the gas; he was pouring more money into those stocks the week they=
 all collapsed. I have speculated that it would be cool if at some point he=
 withdrew a billion dollars of profits and buried them in his backyard, but=
 even after the trial I have never seen any evidence of that.
  [6]
 =E2=80=9CWhat was in it for him,=E2=80=9D the judge asked before the trial=
, and I don=E2=80=99t think there was ever really an answer.=C2=A0It doesn=
=E2=80=99t matter! Manipulating stocks for no reason is illegal, just like =
manipulating them for profit would be. It=E2=80=99s just narratively unsati=
sfying.
