      Greenshoes
   =20
 =20
When a US company does an initial public offering of its stock, there is no=
rmally a =E2=80=9Cgreenshoe.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Let=E2=80=99s say the company pl=
ans to sell 10 million shares in its IPO. The company hires investment bank=
s to sell the stock, they go out and market the stock and take orders, and =
eventually they come back to the company and say =E2=80=9Cwe think you can =
sell your 10 million shares at $20 each.=E2=80=9D The company agrees, the d=
eal is priced, and the banks go off and allocate the stock to the investors=
 who put in orders.But the banks do not allocate 10 million shares to inves=
tors. They allocate 11.5 million shares, 15% more than the size of the offe=
ring.=C2=A0The company sells 10 million shares to the banks for $200 millio=
n, but the banks sell 11.5 million shares to investors for $230 million.
  [7]
 The banks are, effectively,=C2=A0short=C2=A01.5 million shares. Sort of. A=
ctually, in addition to the 10 million shares that it sells to the banks, t=
he company also gives the banks an=C2=A0option=C2=A0to buy another 1.5 mill=
ion shares, at the IPO price, within the next few weeks. The option is call=
ed a =E2=80=9Cgreenshoe option,=E2=80=9D named after the first company to d=
o it.=C2=A0And then the stock opens for trading, and it either trades up or=
 down. Ordinarily it trades up. If the stock ends its first day of trading =
at, say, $27, then the banks come to the company and say =E2=80=9Cthe stock=
 traded well, everything=E2=80=99s great and we=E2=80=99re exercising the g=
reenshoe.=E2=80=9D The company gives the banks the extra 1.5 million shares=
, the banks give the company the extra $30 million, and the number of share=
s issued by the company (11.5 million) matches the number of shares sold in=
 the IPO.Sometimes it trades down, though. If, on the first day, the stock =
falls from $20 to $19.75, the banks will start=C2=A0buying back=C2=A0some o=
f the stock they sold. This has the effect of keeping the price up: If nobo=
dy else is buying the stock, the banks will. They will keep going until the=
y have bought back 1.5 million shares, =E2=80=9Cusing=E2=80=9D the greensho=
e to =E2=80=9Cdefend=E2=80=9D the IPO price. If the banks buy back all 1.5 =
million shares, then they close out their short that way: They never exerci=
se the greenshoe option, the company only issues 10 million shares, and aft=
er the IPO is done only 10 million shares are outstanding. The banks sold 1=
1.5 million and bought back 1.5 million to defend the price.This is called =
=E2=80=9Cstabilization,=E2=80=9D and it is a sort of legal form of market m=
anipulation: The banks that do an IPO are allowed to buy back stock to try =
to stop it falling below the IPO price. It is a longstanding part of US sto=
ck offerings, and bankers will tell companies that it is essential. Because=
 the banks stand ready to defend the IPO price, investors have more confide=
nce that the IPO price is good, and are more likely to buy the IPO. And so =
most US IPOs feature greenshoes: Investors like them, banks insist on them,=
 and companies=C2=A0want their IPOs to go well and don=E2=80=99t want to le=
ave out a feature that investors want. I have never been all that convinced=
 that greenshoes are necessary, and you probably could do an IPO without on=
e, but most companies end up doing the standard thing.Every so often, thoug=
h, the greenshoe leads to a weird result. The IPO prices at $20, and the ne=
xt day it opens for trading at, like, $16. The deal is just mispriced, the =
investors who buy in the IPO are hoping to flip it, there are no real buyer=
s, and the stock immediately falls well below the IPO price. In that case, =
there is not a ton that the banks can do, but they=E2=80=99ll do what they =
can: They buy back the 1.5 million shares, at $16 each, to stop the price g=
oing even lower.The weird result is that they sold those 1.5 million shares=
 for $20 and bought them back at $16, making a profit of $6 million.=C2=A0T=
hey shorted the stock of the IPO they were selling, and made money when it =
went down. That looks bad!And in fact some form of this has happened in sev=
eral high-profile IPOs =E2=80=94=C2=A0including Facebook Inc.=C2=A0and Uber=
 Technologies Inc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and each time there is a little controver=
sy about the fact that the banks make money by pricing IPOs too high and be=
tting against them.Now, this is not a particularly serious controversy, bec=
ause it=E2=80=99s pretty clear that the banks are not doing this nefariousl=
y. If they were, they=E2=80=99d do it more often! In fact, most IPOs are cl=
early priced to go=C2=A0up, and the more frequent complaint is =E2=80=9Cban=
ks underprice IPOs to benefit their investor clients at the expense of the =
IPO companies,=E2=80=9D not =E2=80=9Cbanks overprice IPOs to make money tra=
ding the greenshoe.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Still it=E2=80=99s all a little weird, an=
d companies that pay attention sometimes find it annoying. Why should the b=
anks be able to make money on the greenshoe? Maybe you have to have this me=
chanism =E2=80=94=C2=A0greenshoes, short selling, stabilization, etc. =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0to attract investors to the IPO, but why is it necessary for th=
e=C2=A0banks=C2=A0to profit from it? I once talked to a startup founder who=
 was thinking of going public and who was contemplating demanding that, if =
the banks=C2=A0do=C2=A0make any money trading the greenshoe, they give it b=
ack to the company: Shouldn=E2=80=99t that money belong to the company, not=
 its banks?Well Bill Ackman is actually doing it. Here is the latest prospe=
ctus for Pershing Square USA Ltd., his proposed US public investment vehicl=
e. In the description of the greenshoe, it says: =E2=80=9CTo the extent the=
 Underwriters generate a net profit from purchasing Common Shares at prices=
 below the initial public offering price to close out any syndicate short p=
osition, the Underwriters have agreed to pay any such net profit to the Com=
pany.=E2=80=9D If PSUS falls below its IPO price and the banks make money b=
uying=C2=A0back stock, they have to pay it to PSUS.Now, this is a bit of an=
 odd case. PSUS=E2=80=99s initial public offering price is fixed at $50 per=
 share, and in a sense it can=E2=80=99t really be over- or undervalued: PSU=
S will initially be just a pot of money that Pershing Square will use to in=
vest in companies, so each share will initially represent $50 worth of mone=
y in the pot. The stock might end up trading at a discount or a premium to =
that value =E2=80=94=C2=A0Pershing Square Holdings, its similar European ve=
hicle, trades at about a 20% discount to net asset value, while a more US-f=
riendly vehicle, given Ackman=E2=80=99s track record and social media prese=
nce, could trade at a premium =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it=E2=80=99s not going to =
drop 50% on the first day. (Not investment advice!) The=C2=A0pricing=C2=A0o=
f this IPO is much less uncertain that the pricing of the typical tech star=
tup IPO, so the chances of making a big profit trading the greenshoe are lo=
wer.Nonetheless it=E2=80=99s a precedent. If the banks agree to pay over th=
eir greenshoe profits here, what=E2=80=99s to stop the next tech startup IP=
O company from asking for the same deal? =E2=80=9CNo, PSUS was different, i=
t was a pot of cash, the expected greenshoe profits were zero=E2=80=9D is n=
ot a very good argument: The greenshoe profits are=C2=A0supposed=C2=A0to be=
 zero on every deal, and if the banks make money on the greenshoe it is bec=
ause something has gone wrong. Why should they profit from that?
