The Purdue Pharma LP situation is:=09Purdue Pharma makes opioid painkillers=
 that led to an addiction crisis and killed a lot of people. Various people=
 sued, and Purdue owes them far more money than it has, so it filed for ban=
kruptcy.=09In the years before it went bankrupt, Purdue Pharma kicked out s=
omething like $11.5 billion to its owners, the Sackler family, some of whos=
e members=C2=A0ran the company and were involved in its opioid marketing.=
=09In addition to=C2=A0Purdue=E2=80=99s=C2=A0money, the various victims wan=
t the=C2=A0Sacklers=E2=80=99=C2=A0money, since that money largely comes fro=
m Purdue and since the Sacklers were largely responsible for Purdue=E2=80=
=99s opioid work.=09But suing the Sacklers is complicated: They=E2=80=99re =
rich and have good lawyers and a lot of the money is now offshore or in tru=
sts that will be hard to access.=09So a settlement was worked out: The Sack=
lers would give about $6 billion of their money to the Purdue bankruptcy es=
tate to pay claims, and in exchange no one would be able to sue them anymor=
e. All their opioid liability would go away.=09This is called a =E2=80=9Cno=
nconsensual third-party release=E2=80=9D: Purdue=E2=80=99s bankruptcy=C2=A0=
would end all opioid-related lawsuits against the Sacklers, even though the=
y are not bankrupt themselves.=09A bankruptcy court signed off on this, a d=
istrict court found it was not allowed, an appeals courts found that it was=
, and finally last month the US Supreme Court overruled that decision and f=
ound that it is in fact not allowed. The bankruptcy court can=E2=80=99t jus=
t end all the lawsuits against the Sacklers.=09Now what?Well, part of the a=
nswer is that there are two sorts of claims against the Sacklers. The most =
straightforward=C2=A0ones are=C2=A0Purdue=E2=80=99s=C2=A0claims. The rough =
idea is that bankruptcy courts can travel back in time a bit. When a compan=
y goes bankrupt, you add up its assets and liabilities and then divvy up th=
e money (1) fairly and (2) based on the seniority of claims. So if the comp=
any has $100 of assets, $50 of senior debt, $100 of junior debt and then so=
me shareholders, the bankruptcy court gives the senior creditors 100 cents =
on the dollar, the junior creditors=C2=A050 cents on the dollar, and the sh=
areholders nothing.But if the shareholders paid themselves a dividend the d=
ay before the bankruptcy, that would obviously be cheating: The bankruptcy =
was imminent, and the=C2=A0shareholders are supposed to get nothing! Or eve=
n if the junior creditors got paid off in full the day before the bankruptc=
y =E2=80=94=C2=A0even if they were totally innocent and=C2=A0really owed th=
e money =E2=80=94=C2=A0that=E2=80=99s not fair either, because the company =
was=C2=A0basically=C2=A0bankrupt, and they should be behind the senior cred=
itors in line.And so bankruptcy courts have various ways to claw back money=
 that went out the door=C2=A0before=C2=A0the bankruptcy. We=C2=A0talked the=
 other day about how some customers of Celsius, the bankrupt crypto firm, w=
ithdrew their money shortly before it went bankrupt, and so got back 100 ce=
nts on the dollar, while other customers waited until bankruptcy and will g=
et back less. Celsius is trying to take their money back, under rules about=
 avoidable transfers: If the company is insolvent and pays back some credit=
ors shortly before bankruptcy, and they get more than they would get in ban=
kruptcy, the bankruptcy court can undo those payments and make the creditor=
s give back the money. The court can also claw back =E2=80=9Cfraudulent tra=
nsfers,=E2=80=9D which covers actual fraud =E2=80=94=C2=A0payments=C2=A0tha=
t were made before bankruptcy =E2=80=9Cwith=C2=A0actual intent to hinder, d=
elay, or defraud=E2=80=9D creditors =E2=80=94=C2=A0but also=C2=A0dividends=
=C2=A0made while the company was insolvent. The idea is that, if the compan=
y is going bankrupt, the shareholders should be last in line; if they paid=
=C2=A0themselves before bankruptcy, they have to give the money back.Again,=
 the Sacklers paid themselves $11.5 billion over the years before bankruptc=
y, and there=E2=80=99s some argument that at least some of that money can b=
e clawed back. Also, some of them were officers and directors of Purdue Pha=
rma, which might have claims against them for violating their fiduciary dut=
ies. Intuitively, Purdue Pharma is worth a large negative amount of money d=
ue to the actions of the Sacklers =E2=80=94=C2=A0both in running the compan=
y and in stripping it of cash as the end approached =E2=80=94=C2=A0and so i=
t has various potential lawsuits against them.But there is also another sor=
t of claim: everyone else=E2=80=99s personal claims against the Sacklers fo=
r everything else. There are various legal theories that might make members=
 of the Sackler family personally liable for Purdue Pharma=E2=80=99s opioid=
 marketing, so victims or state attorneys general could sue them under thos=
e theories. Not =E2=80=9Cyou owe this money to Purdue, which owes it to me,=
=E2=80=9D but =E2=80=9Cyou owe this money to me directly.=E2=80=9DThe Supre=
me Court essentially ruled that the bankruptcy court can=E2=80=99t release =
the second category of claims: The Sacklers aren=E2=80=99t bankrupt, so if =
some attorney general wants to bring some personal lawsuit against one of t=
hem, the bankruptcy court can=E2=80=99t stop it. But the bankruptcy court c=
an=C2=A0clearly=C2=A0release the first category of claims: Those claims bel=
ong to Purdue Pharma, and Purdue Pharma is in bankruptcy, and if Purdue Pha=
rma wants to settle a lawsuit against the Sacklers, the bankruptcy court is=
 the court that will sign off on that.The Sacklers don=E2=80=99t want that:=
 They don=E2=80=99t want to settle=C2=A0only Purdue=E2=80=99s claims; they =
want to settle=C2=A0everyone=E2=80=99s=C2=A0claims and get a full release. =
They don=E2=80=99t want to pay 90% of their money to Purdue, only to get su=
ed for another 300% of their money by other people. They want a global sett=
lement. And the Supreme Court said that they can=E2=80=99t get it.To be cle=
ar, Purdue=E2=80=99s bankruptcy estate =E2=80=94=C2=A0the lawyers and judge=
s working on the case, including most of the victims and creditors =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0wanted that too. They wanted a global settlement because that maxi=
mized the amount of money the Sacklers were willing to put in. Without a gl=
obal settlement, the Sacklers will be less inclined to settle any individua=
l case.But that=E2=80=99s not an option anymore, so the obvious next step i=
s for the bankruptcy estate to try to settle=C2=A0its=C2=A0claims against t=
he Sacklers. And the first step in=C2=A0that=C2=A0process is pretty much to=
 rattle some swords and make it clear that (1) Purdue Pharma=C2=A0has=C2=A0=
claims against the Sacklers, (2) those claims are good and big and (3) it w=
ill pursue them aggressively. So the Wall Street Journal reports:Bankrupt o=
pioid maker Purdue Pharma is backing an effort by its top creditors to sue =
members of the Sackler family who own the company over allegations that the=
y illegally transferred billions of dollars to private trusts before Purdue=
=E2=80=99s 2019 bankruptcy filing.The official committee of Purdue=E2=80=99=
s creditors filed a proposed complaint against the Sacklers on Monday after=
 the Supreme Court last month rejected a $6 billion settlement agreement to=
 resolve the mass opioid-related lawsuits against the company=E2=80=99s fam=
ily owners.Purdue supports granting the creditors committee the legal stand=
ing to sue, according to Monday=E2=80=99s filing. The company also is seeki=
ng to restart negotiations with the Sacklers, whose wealth has been estimat=
ed near $11 billion.Here is the proposed complaint, which is quite punchy:T=
o guarantee their family remained ultrawealthy for generations to come, the=
 Sacklers also had to siphon those profits out of the Debtors, and (they ho=
ped) beyond the reach of Purdue=E2=80=99s creditors, including the individu=
al and governmental victims of the opioid crisis that Purdue and the Sackle=
rs helped create and fuel.=C2=A0Indeed, the Sacklers=E2=80=99 efforts to mo=
ve assets out of Purdue and away from its creditors are at the heart of thi=
s Complaint. The experience of Purdue=E2=80=99s guilty plea in 2007 particu=
larly alarmed the Sacklers and drove home the danger that opioid-related li=
tigation could swamp Purdue and threaten their wealth. Just a few days afte=
r entry of the first guilty plea in 2007, the Sacklers panicked and asked e=
ach other, =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re rich? For how long? Until which suits get=
 through to the family?=E2=80=9D A few months later, Peter Boer, a close fa=
mily advisor and soon-to-be Purdue director, advised the Sacklers to =E2=80=
=9Ctake defensive measures=E2=80=9D against Purdue=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cuncap=
ped liabilities,=E2=80=9D including by sending assets overseas. Boer counse=
led the Sacklers to deprive litigants of a =E2=80=9Cdeep pocket=E2=80=9D fr=
om which to recover damages inflicted by Purdue.Consistent with that advice=
, the Sacklers spent the next decade siphoning off the proceeds of their il=
legal marketing and sale of opioids from Purdue just as Boer and others had=
 counseled. The Sacklers transferred billions into an elaborate system of t=
rusts and offshore entities in a manner designed to defraud the Debtors and=
 the Debtors=E2=80=99 creditors and frustrate any effort at recovery by the=
 individuals and governments that have been devastated by Purdue=E2=80=99s =
crimes. The family hoped they had created =E2=80=9Clayers and layers that w=
ould have to be penetrated=E2=80=9D before litigation could threaten the =
=E2=80=9Cvast fortune=E2=80=9D the family had built. Immediately following =
the 2007 guilty plea, the Sacklers dramatically increased distributions fro=
m the company, transferring more than $11.5 billion in cash and property of=
fshore and to spendthrift trusts in less than a decade.=C2=A0And the Journa=
l quotes the Sacklers=E2=80=99 punchy response:Representatives for the fami=
lies of the late Mortimer Sackler and the late Raymond Sackler said the cre=
ditors=E2=80=99 filing =E2=80=9Cis riddled with factual errors, ignores tha=
t about half the money was paid in taxes and is contrary to the goal of wor=
king together towards a resolution that provides billions of dollars for co=
mmunities and people in need.=E2=80=9DBut all of this is probably part of n=
egotiations. Purdue Pharma wrote a statement supporting the lawsuit, saying=
 that =E2=80=9Cthe Debtors=E2=80=99 claims against third parties are the es=
tates=E2=80=99 most valuable assets=E2=80=94they underlay the settlement un=
der which the Sacklers had previously agreed to pay $5.5-6 billion.=E2=80=
=9D But it adds that that =E2=80=9Cthe Debtors are hopeful that mediation w=
ill lead to a consensual resolution of these chapter 11 cases.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0Basically: The Sacklers agreed to pay up to $6 billion of their own mone=
y to opioid victims, because they figured that was better than fighting a m=
illion lawsuits. In exchange, they wanted those lawsuits to all go away. Th=
e Supreme Court said that that is not allowed. Now, Purdue Pharma would lik=
e the Sacklers to pay up to $6 billion of their own money to opioid victims=
, because they figure that is better than fighting=C2=A0one=C2=A0lawsuit =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0the biggest and most straightforward one =E2=80=94=C2=A0from=
 Purdue itself. That negotiation starts by threatening the lawsuit.
