</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a retail stock investor in =
the US, you have a broker. Your broker is a company =E2=80=94=C2=A0Robinhoo=
d or Charles Schwab or E*Trade =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is in the business of ha=
ving account relationships with retail investors. It advertises to attract =
your business, it has a nice website and app for you to make trades, it acc=
epts transfers from your bank so you can buy stocks, it sends you account s=
tatements and keeps track of your stocks for you.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">But what the broker typically does not do is=C2=A0<em>trade st=
ocks for you</em>.=C2=A0If you want to trade stocks, you go to your broker=
=E2=80=99s app and click the buttons for =E2=80=9Cbuy 100 shares of XYZ,=E2=
=80=9D and the broker=E2=80=99s computer gets the order, and then it ships =
the order out to someone=C2=A0<em>else</em>, some=C2=A0<em>different=C2=A0<=
/em>company, called a =E2=80=9Cmarket maker,=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-i=
ndex" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; dis=
play: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> whose job is to get you the stock at the best available price.=C2=A0So=
metimes this will involve sending your order on to the New York Stock Excha=
nge, or some other trading venue: The market maker buys 100 shares of XYZ o=
n the exchange at the market price and then hands them over to you. Often, =
though, the market maker will instead sell you the stock out of its invento=
ry: It is in the business of trading stocks for its own account, so when it=
 gets your order to buy 100 shares of XYZ, it will sell you 100 shares of X=
YZ as a principal, charging you slightly less than the market price on the =
exchange.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You do=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>hav=
e a direct account relationship with the market maker, and you might not kn=
ow who the market maker is on any stock trade that you do, though you can g=
et some general idea from public disclosures. If you are a customer of Robi=
nhood, for instance, your stock orders are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/36027023.195406/aHR0cHM6Ly9jZG4ucm9iaW5ob29kLmNvbS=
9hc3NldHMvcm9iaW5ob29kL2xlZ2FsL1JIUyUyMFNFQyUyMFJ1bGUlMjA2MDYlMjBhbmQlMjA2M=
DclMjBEaXNjbG9zdXJlLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB547d5df1" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">probab=
ly being executed</a> by Virtu Americas, Citadel Securities, Jane Street Ca=
pital, G1 Execution Services or Two Sigma Securities. That=E2=80=99s a pret=
ty typical list; those are some of the biggest market makers for retail sto=
ck trades.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why is there this division of la=
bor? Well, why is there any division of labor? The people who run Robinhood=
 and Charles Schwab are in the business of advertising and providing custom=
er service to retail investors; the people who run Virtu and Citadel Securi=
