ion for units where profits are getting eroded by stiffer capital rules, co=
mpetitive pressures to lower fees and the need to make costly upgrades. Fir=
ms including Deutsche Bank AG have responded to narrowing margins in stock =
trading in recent years by shuttering some desks, ceding market share to to=
p players such as JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. and Goldman Sachs Group Inc.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CBanks and brokers are getting squeeze=
d on both ends, which is where we are seeing customer service deteriorating=
,=E2=80=9D said Jesse Forster, a senior analyst of market structure and tec=
hnology at Coalition Greenwich. =E2=80=9CInvestors are not getting their pr=
oper trading coverage, and they have been vocal about that.=E2=80=9D</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Citadel Securities=E2=80=99 move underscores the =
ambitions afoot inside billionaire Griffin=E2=80=99s massive trading operat=
ion, led by Chief Executive Officer=C2=A0Peng Zhao. The firm would likely p=
itch such partnerships as a way for embattled banks and brokerages to shave=
 costs and offer customers better pricing with superior technology.</p></bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It used to be that, if you wanted to =
trade an exotic derivative or sell a portfolio of high-yield bonds, you cou=
