5px;">Greenshoes</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When a US company does an initial publ=
ic offering of its stock, there is normally a =E2=80=9Cgreenshoe.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0Let=E2=80=99s say the company plans to sell 10 million shares in its =
IPO. The company hires investment banks to sell the stock, they go out and =
market the stock and take orders, and eventually they come back to the comp=
any and say =E2=80=9Cwe think you can sell your 10 million shares at $20 ea=
ch.=E2=80=9D The company agrees, the deal is priced, and the banks go off a=
nd allocate the stock to the investors who put in orders.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">But the banks do not allocate 10 million shares to investors=
. They allocate 11.5 million shares, 15% more than the size of the offering=
.=C2=A0The company sells 10 million shares to the banks for $200 million, b=
ut the banks sell 11.5 million shares to investors for $230 million.<a clas=
s=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent =
!important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a> The banks are, effectively,=C2=A0<em>short=C2=A0</em>1.5 million share=
s. Sort of. Actually, in addition to the 10 million shares that it sells to=
 the banks, the company also gives the banks an=C2=A0<em>option</em>=C2=A0t=
o buy another 1.5 million shares, at the IPO price, within the next few wee=
ks. The option is called a =E2=80=9Cgreenshoe option,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36027023.195406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cubWFuaGF0dGFuc3RyZWV0Y2FwaXRhbC5jb20vZmFxL2Zvci1mdW5kcmFpc2Vycy1mb3ItaW52Z=
XN0b3JzL3doYXQtZ3JlZW5zaG9lLXVzZWQtaXBvcw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe5c51ec4=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;">named after</a> the first company to do it.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">And then the stock opens for trading, and it either trades=
 up or down. Ordinarily it trades up. If the stock ends its first day of tr=
ading at, say, $27, then the banks come to the company and say =E2=80=9Cthe=
 stock traded well, everything=E2=80=99s great and we=E2=80=99re exercising=
 the greenshoe.=E2=80=9D The company gives the banks the extra 1.5 million =
shares, the banks give the company the extra $30 million, and the number of=
 shares issued by the company (11.5 million) matches the number of shares s=
old in the IPO.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sometimes it trades down, t=
hough. If, on the first day, the stock falls from $20 to $19.75, the banks =
will start=C2=A0<em>buying back=C2=A0</em>some of the stock they sold. This=
 has the effect of keeping the price up: If nobody else is buying the stock=
, the banks will. They will keep going until they have bought back 1.5 mill=
ion shares, =E2=80=9Cusing=E2=80=9D the greenshoe to =E2=80=9Cdefend=E2=80=
=9D the IPO price. If the banks buy back all 1.5 million shares, then they =
close out their short that way: They never exercise the greenshoe option, t=
he company only issues 10 million shares, and after the IPO is done only 10=
 million shares are outstanding. The banks sold 11.5 million and bought bac=
k 1.5 million to defend the price.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is =
called =E2=80=9Cstabilization,=E2=80=9D and it is a sort of <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36027023.195406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTYtMTEtMjUvYXBwZWFscy1jb3VydC1j=
b25jbHVkZXMtdGhhdC1pcG9zLWFyZS1sZWdhbD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNzExMjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ=
1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA3MTEmdX=
RtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8e5d4848" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
legal form of market manipulation</a>: The banks that do an IPO are allowed=
 to buy back stock to try to stop it falling below the IPO price. It is a l=
ongstanding part of US stock offerings, and bankers will tell companies tha=
t it is essential. Because the banks stand ready to defend the IPO price, i=
nvestors have more confidence that the IPO price is good, and are more like=
ly to buy the IPO. And so most US IPOs feature greenshoes: Investors like t=
hem, banks insist on them, and companies=C2=A0want their IPOs to go well an=
d don=E2=80=99t want to leave out a feature that investors want. I have nev=
er been all that convinced that greenshoes are necessary, and you probably =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36027023.195406/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS92aWV3L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDMtMTYvc3BvdGlme=
S13aWxsLXNraXAtYS1sb3Qtb2YtaXBvLWVzc2VudGlhbHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDcxMTI0X01PTkVZ=
U1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQ=
wNzExJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB85e69341" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">could do an IPO without one</a>, but most companies end up doing the =
standard thing.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Every so often, though, the=
 greenshoe leads to a weird result. The IPO prices at $20, and the next day=
 it opens for trading at, like, $16. The deal is just mispriced, the invest=
ors who buy in the IPO are hoping to flip it, there are no real buyers, and=
 the stock immediately falls well below the IPO price. In that case, there =
is not a ton that the banks can do, but they=E2=80=99ll do what they can: T=
hey buy back the 1.5 million shares, at $16 each, to stop the price going e=
ven lower.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The weird result is that they so=
ld those 1.5 million shares for $20 and bought them back at $16, making a p=
rofit of $6 million.=C2=A0<em>They shorted the stock of the IPO they were s=
elling, and made money when it went down. </em>That looks bad!</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And in fact some form of this has happened in several =
high-profile IPOs =E2=80=94=C2=A0including <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/36027023.195406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucmV1dGVycy5jb20vYX=
J0aWNsZS9pZFVTMjg2NzAzNTA5NS8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB27448b24" itemprop=
