kground-color: #ccc;">not a particularly serious controversy</a>, because i=
t=E2=80=99s pretty clear that the banks are not doing this nefariously. If =
they were, they=E2=80=99d do it more often! In fact, most IPOs are clearly =
priced to go=C2=A0<em>up</em>, and the more frequent complaint is =E2=80=9C=
banks underprice IPOs to benefit their investor clients at the expense of t=
he IPO companies,=E2=80=9D not =E2=80=9Cbanks overprice IPOs to make money =
trading the greenshoe.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still=
 it=E2=80=99s all a little weird, and companies that pay attention sometime=
s find it annoying. Why should the banks be able to make money on the green=
shoe? Maybe you have to have this mechanism =E2=80=94=C2=A0greenshoes, shor=
t selling, stabilization, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0to attract investors to the I=
PO, but why is it necessary for the=C2=A0<em>banks=C2=A0</em>to profit from=
 it? I once talked to a startup founder who was thinking of going public an=
d who was contemplating demanding that, if the banks=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>=
make any money trading the greenshoe, they give it back to the company: Sho=
uldn=E2=80=99t that money belong to the company, not its banks?</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well Bill Ackman is actually doing it. Here is the lat=
est <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/36027023.19540=
