7ceef4b8524a319a23cB3431ddb8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the description of the greenshoe</a>,=
 it says: =E2=80=9CTo the extent the Underwriters generate a net profit fro=
m purchasing Common Shares at prices below the initial public offering pric=
e to close out any syndicate short position, the Underwriters have agreed t=
o pay any such net profit to the Company.=E2=80=9D If PSUS falls below its =
IPO price and the banks make money buying=C2=A0back stock, they have to pay=
 it to PSUS.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, this is a bit of an odd c=
ase. PSUS=E2=80=99s initial public offering price is fixed at $50 per share=
, and in a sense it can=E2=80=99t really be over- or undervalued: PSUS will=
 initially be just a pot of money that Pershing Square will use to invest i=
n companies, so each share will initially represent $50 worth of money in t=
he pot. The stock might end up trading at a discount or a premium to that v=
alue =E2=80=94=C2=A0Pershing Square Holdings, its similar European vehicle,=
 trades at about a 20% discount to net asset value, while a more US-friendl=
y vehicle, given Ackman=E2=80=99s track record and social media presence, c=
ould trade at a premium =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it=E2=80=99s not going to drop 5=
0% on the first day. (Not investment advice!) The=C2=A0<em>pricing=C2=A0</e=
m>of this IPO is much less uncertain that the pricing of the typical tech s=
tartup IPO, so the chances of making a big profit trading the greenshoe are=
 lower.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nonetheless it=E2=80=99s a preceden=
t. If the banks agree to pay over their greenshoe profits here, what=E2=80=
=99s to stop the next tech startup IPO company from asking for the same dea=
l? =E2=80=9CNo, PSUS was different, it was a pot of cash, the expected gree=
nshoe profits were zero=E2=80=9D is not a very good argument: The greenshoe=
